00:01:34.090 --> 00:01:37.750
is also a committed and
distinguished administrator,

00:01:37.750 --> 00:01:41.950
having served since 2003
as Director of the National

00:01:41.950 --> 00:01:44.980
Institute on Drug
Abuse, and before that,

00:01:44.980 --> 00:01:48.770
in senior roles at the
Brookhaven National Laboratory.

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:52.720
Nora is renowned for her
pioneering use of brain imaging

00:01:52.720 --> 00:01:57.190
to study the toxic effects and
addictive properties of drugs

00:01:57.190 --> 00:01:58.570
of abuse.

00:01:58.570 --> 00:02:02.410
Nora's research was instrumental
in showing that addiction

00:02:02.410 --> 00:02:05.950
is a chronic disease of
the brain, an insight

00:02:05.950 --> 00:02:10.720
with major implications both
for psychiatry and for policy.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:14.290
This body of work has been
critical to identifying

00:02:14.290 --> 00:02:16.720
the neurochemical
mechanisms of the brain that

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:19.330
play a role in
individual vulnerability

00:02:19.330 --> 00:02:22.270
to substance use disorders.

00:02:22.270 --> 00:02:25.330
It would be hard to
overstate the importance

00:02:25.330 --> 00:02:27.190
of this research.

00:02:27.190 --> 00:02:29.980
The brain disease
model of addiction

00:02:29.980 --> 00:02:34.120
represented a fundamental change
from the previously widespread

00:02:34.120 --> 00:02:37.210
view that substance
abuse disorders

00:02:37.210 --> 00:02:41.290
reflect weak willpower
or moral failing.

00:02:41.290 --> 00:02:43.900
Among the outcomes of
this paradigm shift

00:02:43.900 --> 00:02:46.960
was the passage of the Mental
Health Parity and Addiction

00:02:46.960 --> 00:02:51.370
Act of 2008, which required
health insurance providers

00:02:51.370 --> 00:02:55.640
to offer the same types of
coverage for mental health,

00:02:55.640 --> 00:02:59.890
including addiction, that they
provide for other diseases.

00:02:59.890 --> 00:03:03.190
Nora's work has also been
central to our understanding

00:03:03.190 --> 00:03:08.950
of the neurobiology of
obesity, of ADHD, and of aging.

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:12.610
In her lecture today Nora will
discuss brain imaging studies

00:03:12.610 --> 00:03:16.450
in investigating the effects of
sleep deprivation highlighting

00:03:16.450 --> 00:03:19.900
important links between
sleep, and addiction,

00:03:19.900 --> 00:03:22.520
and other diseases.

00:03:22.520 --> 00:03:25.720
Now the story of how Nora came
to do this kind of research

00:03:25.720 --> 00:03:27.370
is unusual.

00:03:27.370 --> 00:03:30.460
Nora grew up in Mexico
City in the house

00:03:30.460 --> 00:03:33.820
where her great
grandfather, Leon Trotsky,

00:03:33.820 --> 00:03:38.440
lived in exile until his
assassination in 1940.

00:03:38.440 --> 00:03:41.650
After graduating at the top
of her class in medicine

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:43.990
at the National
University of Mexico,

00:03:43.990 --> 00:03:47.950
Nora became fascinated by
a brain imaging technology

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:51.540
called positron emission
tomography, or PET for short.

00:03:54.350 --> 00:03:58.000
So Nora traveled to New York
University School of Medicine

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:01.210
where researchers were doing
PET imaging in collaboration

00:04:01.210 --> 00:04:03.700
with the Brookhaven
National Laboratory.

00:04:03.700 --> 00:04:06.920
Nora was already impressive
by her mid-twenties,

00:04:06.920 --> 00:04:10.430
and these scientists seized
the opportunity to hire her.

00:04:10.430 --> 00:04:14.800
Nora then enrolled in NYU'S
residency program in psychiatry

00:04:14.800 --> 00:04:19.269
and used PET imaging to study
brain tumors and schizophrenia.

00:04:19.269 --> 00:04:21.790
She soon earned the
Laughlin Fellowship Award

00:04:21.790 --> 00:04:23.860
from the American
College of Psychiatrists,

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:26.860
which is given annually
to outstanding psychiatric

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:30.860
residents deemed likely to
make a significant contribution

00:04:30.860 --> 00:04:32.380
to the field.

00:04:32.380 --> 00:04:36.010
Nora next joined the faculty of
the University of Texas Health

00:04:36.010 --> 00:04:38.980
Science Center at
Houston intending

00:04:38.980 --> 00:04:42.310
to continue her research
into schizophrenia.

00:04:42.310 --> 00:04:45.400
When she discovered a shortage
of appropriate patients

00:04:45.400 --> 00:04:48.700
at the University Hospital,
she had a novel idea

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:50.620
to use the same
imaging technique

00:04:50.620 --> 00:04:53.890
to study patients admitted
for psychosis from having

00:04:53.890 --> 00:04:55.870
taken cocaine.

00:04:55.870 --> 00:04:58.930
This investigation led to
the breakthrough discovery

00:04:58.930 --> 00:05:02.080
that cocaine, which was
generally considered safe

00:05:02.080 --> 00:05:05.170
at the time, is in
fact toxic and damages

00:05:05.170 --> 00:05:07.720
the brain by
decreasing blood flow.

00:05:07.720 --> 00:05:09.940
Her findings went
so against the grain

00:05:09.940 --> 00:05:13.650
that no science journal would
publish them for three years.

00:05:13.650 --> 00:05:16.300
Nora's commitment to
gather data and follow them

00:05:16.300 --> 00:05:19.510
where they ever they lead,
even when her results challenge

00:05:19.510 --> 00:05:21.850
the public and
scientific consensus,

00:05:21.850 --> 00:05:23.830
has remained the
keystone to what

00:05:23.830 --> 00:05:26.170
makes her work so compelling.

00:05:26.170 --> 00:05:28.750
After moving on to Brookhaven
National Laboratory

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:31.390
in the State University of
New York at Stony Brook,

00:05:31.390 --> 00:05:33.940
Nora served in a number
of leadership roles

00:05:33.940 --> 00:05:37.930
while continuing her ambitious
research program on addiction.

00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:39.970
In her current
position as director

00:05:39.970 --> 00:05:42.260
of the National
Institute on Drug Abuse,

00:05:42.260 --> 00:05:45.490
Nora's advocacy for new
policies and treatments

00:05:45.490 --> 00:05:49.590
based on sound science
has been vital.

00:05:49.590 --> 00:05:52.930
But she is also an
inspiring model of someone

00:05:52.930 --> 00:05:56.230
who effectively combines
scientific research,

00:05:56.230 --> 00:06:00.070
institutional leadership,
and policy advocacy.

